Analysis of White Wines

Kevin Turner

January 24, 2019

The data set contains 4,898 white wines with 11 attributes on quantifying the chemical properties of each wine and 1 attribute providing a quality score as determined by at least 3 expert wine tasters. Quality was rated on a scale of 0 to 10.

Let’s have a look at the attributes available within this dataset.

##  [1] "fixed.acidity"        "volatile.acidity"     "citric.acid"         
##  [4] "residual.sugar"       "chlorides"            "free.sulfur.dioxide" 
##  [7] "total.sulfur.dioxide" "density"              "pH"                  
## [10] "sulphates"            "alcohol"              "quality"

Description of attributes:

  1. fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3): most acids involved with wine are fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)

  2. volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3): the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste

  3. citric acid (g / dm^3): found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines

  4. residual sugar (g / dm^3): the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet

  5. chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3): the amount of salt in the wine

  6. free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3): the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

  7. total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3): amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine

  8. density (g / cm^3): the density of wine is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content

  9. pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale

  10. sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3): a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant

  11. alcohol (% by volume): the percent alcohol content of the wine

  12. quality (score between 0 and 10) - Output variable (based on sensory data)

After reviewing the statistical information there are a few interesting observations. Some of the attributes have large gaps between thier 3rd Quartile and Max values. We’ll look a bit more at those in a minute.

First, lets take a quick view of how the wines rated by quality.

The quality of the wines we are anlyzing look to follow a nice bell curve with most wines falling in the middle of the scale and a one or two on each end.

Now lets see a quick visual overview of the rest of our data points.

From the histograms above we can see that some of our data is close to normal distribution while other data is right skewed. There are no attributes that are left skewed in the dataset. We can aso deduce that there are outliers in several attributes based on the bin widths and what appears to be large empty space to the right of the bars.

Lets have a closer look at a chlorides and free.sulfur.dioxide, two of the attributes that appear to have extreme outliers.

In both the above histograms the major outliers have been labeled to make them easier to identify. Major outliers are calculated based on Third Quartile + 3 * Inner Quartile Range.

The below histogram is for pH, an attribute that more closely follows a normal distribution. As evident by the lack of any labeled bins, there were no major outliers found here.

Univariate Analysis

The dataset contains 4,898 observations and 12 variables. 11 variables are of the numeric data type and 1 variable is an integer.

The main feature of interest in this dataset would be the Quality score. Throughout this analysis we will investigate how the other variables contribute, positive or negative, to that quality score.

In order to organize the data in a way that was easier to display as an overview the tidyr library was used to create a new dataframe. Utilizing this library value:key pairs were created for each variable and value. This process is defined as taking “wide”" data, many columns and fewer rows, and making it “long”, many rows and fewer columns. The resulting dataframe’s structure contains 53,878 observations and 3 variables.

Most distributions with in this dataset can be described as right skewed, or close to a normal. Several attributes in the dataset do contain major outliers, however the values are within an acceptable range for the process so for the purpose of this analysis they will be included.

Bivariate Plots

Let’s see if we can make any determinations as to whether any of these attributes have an affect on the quality of the wines.

We’ll start by looking at a visual overview of how each attribute value correlates to the quality rating. We’ll use scatterplots and smooth curves to help us more easuly identify trends.

Very interesting. It appears that some attributes like alcohol, sulphates, and pH may have very little affect on the quality of the wine as evident by the relativly flat smooth curve.

However, a few atributes do stand out. free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide appear to have a sweet spot for higher quality scores and values outside that range, lower or higher, seems to negatively affect quality. Additionally, it appears the the higher the volatile.acidity the lower the quality of wine. This makes sense since too high of levels of volatile.acidity can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste.

We are going to take a closer look at these attributes.

Here we can more clearly see that there is a negative trend with free.sulfur.dioxide and quality. When free.sulfur.dioxide values are with in a specific range of about 0 - 100, quality does not seem affected much, however once the value start getting beyond 100 there is a noticable degredation in the quality of the wine.

So what has an effect on free.sulfur.dioxide? Let’s again take a visual overview of our attributes, but this time focusing on how they compare to free.sulfur.dioxide.

Clearly more free.sulfur.dioxide leads to more total.sulfur.dioxide. This makes perfect sense. There are a couple other trends that look interesting, pH and sulphates, but at first glance it seems that the outliers may have some some influence here.

Since there is a strong relationship between free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide, lets explore it a little more.

Looking at this relationship more closely we can see that even excluding the outlier we have a postive relationsip between free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide.

But does this mean anything? Let’s keep going by looking at how total.sulfur.dioxide is affected by the other attributes.

of course we can see the relationship between free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide as we explored earlier. Also seen earlier with free.sulfur.dioxide we can see that there is a positive trend with sulphates a depicted below.

Since sulphates is a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels it seems logical that the more sulphates found in the wine then higher levels of free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfer.dioxide will exist.

Bivariate Analysis

We explored the relationship between seraval attributes through this bivariate analysis.

Beginning with an overview of how each attribute affected qaulity, we identified a couple attributes to take a deeper look at. From there we explored free.sulfur.dioxide, which led is to total.sulfur.dioxide, then finally to sulphates.

We explored how each attribute affected the next and can conclude that the more sulphates added to a wine increases the free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxie levels which can have a negative impact on the quality of wine.

Multivariate Plots Section

In previous sections of the analysis we explored our data set and the indvidual attributes it contains. We also looked at how attrubites affect other attributes. Now let see multiple attributes together. The first thing we will look at is how each attribute correlates with the others.

So our dataset contains some postive corellations, identified in purple, and some negative correlations, identified in red. We can see the strongest postive correlation is between residial.sugar and denstiy. The strongest negative correlation is between alcohol and density. There are also a number of non-significant correlations marke by the X over the box.

Multivariate Analysis

It’s interesting to see that there are many more positive correlations between attributes within the dataset than negative ones. As certain levels of some attributes rise it directtly affects these other attributes in a positive way. As an example, though this probably seems intuitive, if there are more residual.sugar then it is expected that the wine will have more density.

As the Quality Score was the primary focus of this dataset, it was a little surprising to see that citric.acid, something I previously thought was a large component in the taste of wine, has no real correlation to the quality.

Final Plots and Summary

We’ve spent a bit of time exploring the dataset. We learned a lot and came to the conclusion that Quality Score was the main attribute to focus on.

We began by taking a look at the details of the other attributes through an overview of thier histograms.

We continued our analysis by looking at how these attributes affected our Quality Score by looking at scatterplots and smooth curves.

Finally we looked at the correlation between each attribute and the other attributes in the dataset.
